thread.title: Aust dollar lower in late trade
thread.title_full: Aust dollar lower in late trade | Business Spectator

author: AAP
title: Aust dollar lower in late trade
text:
The Australian dollar is slightly weaker due to mixed economic data from China.
At 1700 AEDT on Monday, the currency was trading at 72.73 US cents, down from 72.90 cents on Friday.
China's economic growth slowed to 6.9 per cent in the third quarter of 2015, which was the worst rate of deceleration in more than six years, but still marginally above market expectations.
National Australia Bank global co-head of FX strategy Ray Attrill said the number initially gave the Australian dollar a boost.
"It had allayed some fears about an even sharper deceleration in Chinese growth and that carried the Aussie higher," he said.
However, mixed signals from other Chinese data released on Monday then pulled the currency back.
Retail sales rose 10.9 per cent in September, marginally stronger than the previous month's gain.
But industrial production, a measure of output at factories, workshops and mines, rose 5.7 per cent year-on-year in September, a sharp drop on the 6.1 per cent increase recorded in August.
At 1700 AEDT, the Australian dollar was at 86.77 Japanese yen, down from Friday's close of 86.86 yen, and at 63.98 euro cents, down from 64.05 euro cents.
Meanwhile, the Australian bond market was flat.
At 1630 AEDT, the December 2015 10-year bond futures contract was trading at 97.375 (implying a yield of 2.625 per cent), unchanged from Friday.
The December 2015 three-year bond futures contract was at 98.210 (1.790 per cent), also unchanged.
